{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503519"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:02:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:02:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2038"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2038"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.7,0.06,0.05,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2038"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101503"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2038"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2038"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83942"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1021"},{"type":"tags","id":"3014"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15860"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42441"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101503"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her boyfriend, who is concerned about her weight and eating habits. He reports that she often skips meals and is very selective about what she eats. On further questioning, they both deny any vomiting after meals, excessive exercise, or laxative use. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears underweight. Her height is 175 cm and weight is 45 kg. Her pulse rate is 60/min and blood pressure 100/60 mmHg. Investigations are ordered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be seen in this patient\u0027s investigation results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperkalaemia","Hypokalaemia","Shortened QT interval","Hyperthyroidism","Decreased growth hormone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with anorexia nervosa, specifically the restricting subtype. The most likely biochemical abnormality in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypokalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, which is one of the most common electrolyte disturbances in anorexia nervosa. Hypokalaemia can result from inadequate dietary intake and, in some cases, from purging behaviours (though not reported in this patient).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperkalaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with anorexia nervosa. In fact, low potassium levels are more common due to malnutrition and, in some cases, purging behaviours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eshortened QT interval\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of anorexia nervosa. Instead, QT prolongation is more commonly observed, which can increase the risk of cardiac arrhythmias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperthyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically seen in anorexia nervosa. In contrast, hypothyroidism or euthyroid sick syndrome is more common, reflecting the body\u0027s adaptation to a low-energy state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased growth hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of anorexia nervosa. Paradoxically, growth hormone levels are often elevated in anorexia as a response to the fasting state, although this doesn\u0027t lead to increased growth due to associated resistance to its effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnorexia nervosa is associated with numerous medical complications affecting multiple organ systems. These can include haematological changes (e.g., leukopaenia, thrombocytopaenia), renal disturbances (e.g., hypokalaemia, hypochloraemia, hypomagnesaemia), cardiac abnormalities (e.g., bradycardia, hypotension, QT prolongation), and endocrine disruptions (e.g., hypothyroidism, hypoglycaemia, low gonadotropins). It\u0027s important to note that while these complications can be severe, most are reversible with appropriate weight restoration and nutritional rehabilitation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypokalaemia is one of the most common biochemical changes in anorexia nervosa.","Anorexia nervosa is associated with various medical complications, including electrolyte disturbances, cardiovascular changes, and endocrine abnormalities.","Most medical complications of anorexia nervosa are reversible with weight gain and nutritional rehabilitation."],"references":["Mehler PS, Brown C. Anorexia nervosa - medical complications. J Eat Disord. 2015;3:11. Available at: https://jeatdisord.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s40337-015-0040-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83942"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2038"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83942"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T12:36:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T12:37:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2038"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101503"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":